ODE V.

Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa was a distinguished general, and so much esteemed by Augustus, that he gave him his daughter Julia in marriage. Agrippa wished his achievements to be celebrated by Horace, who, while he excuses himself from the more laborious and responsible task of writing a for- mal poem, ingeniously pays him the most flattering compliment. He intimates that Agrippa’s martial glory deserves the strains of a lostier genius than his own, that his was the lyric muse, and fit only for light 01· trifling subjects 3 but that Varius, gifted with the sublimest inspirations of the epic muse, would sing his praises in strains worthy of the subject.

Most commentators have thought this ode merely an'excuse of Horace for not doing that which he had no disposition to do. But the fulness of the praises bestowed renders this conjecture superfluous. It is probably only an instance, among many, of his artfully performing what he pretends to decline doin .
